docs.abstract: Women are playing leading roles across the political spectrum in the state, with Democrats hoping to flip the Arizona legislature and Republicans fielding strong female candidates at all levels.
docs.snippet: Women are playing leading roles across the political spectrum in the state, with Democrats hoping to flip the Arizona legislature and Republicans fielding strong female candidates at all levels.
docs.lead_paragraph: PHOENIX — Melinda Merkel Iyer was a stay-at-home mother and political novice when Donald J. Trump was elected president. She didn’t sleep that night. The next day, Ms. Iyer pored over the state legislature’s website, discovered how to track bills, and soon turned her notes on thwarting conservative proposals into a do-it-yourself newsletter.

headline.main: Year of the Woman? In Arizona, It’s Women, Plural, and It’s Both Parties
headline.print_headline: Left, Right and Center, Women of Arizona Reshape the Debate

docs.abstract: The former coal executive faced a concerted effort by Republicans to stop him, including an appeal from President Trump. Patrick Morrisey, the state’s attorney general, won the party’s nomination.
docs.snippet: The former coal executive faced a concerted effort by Republicans to stop him, including an appeal from President Trump. Patrick Morrisey, the state’s attorney general, won the party’s nomination.
docs.lead_paragraph: CHARLESTON, W.Va. — Don Blankenship, a former coal baron who went to prison for his role in a deadly mine disaster, was soundly defeated in the West Virginia Republican Senate primary on Tuesday, according to The Associated Press, after President Trump and other Republicans urged voters to reject him.

headline.main: Don Blankenship Loses West Virginia Republican Primary for Senate
headline.print_headline: Ex-Coal Baron Jailed Over Mine Blast Loses West Virginia Primary

docs.abstract: As Virginia faces the possibility that its executive branch could include two men who once mocked African-Americans and a third accused of rape, Democratic women are divided over how to move forward.
docs.snippet: As Virginia faces the possibility that its executive branch could include two men who once mocked African-Americans and a third accused of rape, Democratic women are divided over how to move forward.
docs.lead_paragraph: RICHMOND, Va. — To Constance Cordovilla, the president of the Virginia National Organization for Women, the two sexual assault allegations against Lt. Gov. Justin E. Fairfax are not just grounds for him to resign — the detailed claims also demand that women side with his accusers.

headline.main: Unmistakable Divide Among Women in Virginia Over Accusations Against Fairfax
headline.print_headline: Distinct Divide Among Virginia Women Over Claims Against Lt. Governor

byline.original: By Jonathan Martin and Michael Wines

docs.abstract: Influential liberal donors and operatives are working with Never Trump Republicans to blunt what they view as the president’s threat to democracy.
docs.snippet: Influential liberal donors and operatives are working with Never Trump Republicans to blunt what they view as the president’s threat to democracy.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Since Donald J. Trump began dominating American politics more than two years ago, Democrats concerned about his policies and behavior have taken solace in a group of influential Republicans who have consistently assailed the president as anathema to the values of their party, and the country more broadly.

headline.main: Concerned by Trump, Some Republicans Quietly Align With Democrats
headline.print_headline: Broad Base of Donors for Republicans Who Turned Away From Trump

docs.abstract: Mr. Weld, the former governor of Massachusetts, is unlikely to pose a major threat to Trump and he is in some ways an incongruous figure to leap into the Republican presidential fray.
docs.snippet: Mr. Weld, the former governor of Massachusetts, is unlikely to pose a major threat to Trump and he is in some ways an incongruous figure to leap into the Republican presidential fray.
docs.lead_paragraph: William F. Weld, the maverick former governor of Massachusetts, announced on Friday that he would form an exploratory committee to challenge President Trump for the Republican Party’s 2020 nomination, presenting himself as a dissident voice in a political party that has abandoned its mainstream roots.

headline.main: Bill Weld Will Challenge Trump for 2020 Republican Nomination
headline.print_headline: Ex-Governor Throws Hat In, Opening Way To G.O.P. Race

docs.abstract: Antonio Delgado is trying to unseat John Faso, a Republican incumbent in New York.
docs.snippet: Antonio Delgado is trying to unseat John Faso, a Republican incumbent in New York.
docs.lead_paragraph: RHINEBECK, N.Y. — Antonio Delgado is a lot of things: a Rhodes Scholar, a graduate of Harvard Law School, a former lawyer at one of the country’s largest lobbying firms, and now the Democratic nominee for Congress in New York’s tossup 19th District, which stretches throughout the Hudson Valley and Catskills regions.

headline.main: A Congressional Candidate Used to Be a Rapper. Will It Matter?
headline.print_headline: His Rival Was a Rapper, and a Congressman Tries to Make It an Issue

docs.abstract: The Republican candidate, who is also the secretary of state, defended his office after a report that registrations for more than 50,000 voters had been placed on a “pending” list.
docs.snippet: The Republican candidate, who is also the secretary of state, defended his office after a report that registrations for more than 50,000 voters had been placed on a “pending” list.
docs.lead_paragraph: Tensions escalated in the already bitter race to be Georgia’s next governor on Thursday after reports that the state had placed tens of thousands of voters’ registrations on a “pending” list, fueling charges of voter suppression and election rigging.

headline.main: Complaints of Voter Suppression Loom Over Georgia Governor’s Race
headline.print_headline: List of 53,000 Stalled Voters Inflames Georgia Race
